&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; What does TFP stand for?
&gt; 
&gt; Donald Holliday
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; -----Original Message-----
&gt; From: J. B. Rainsberger [mailto:jbrains762@...]
&gt; Sent: Sunday, October 21, 2001 6:09 AM
&gt; To: junit@yahoogroups.com
&gt; Subject: [junit] Unit test for infinite loop
&gt; 
&gt; 
&gt; &gt; How does one write a unit test that exposes an infinte loop?  Well,
&gt; writing
&gt; &gt; one that exposes it isn&#39;t hard.  How do you expose it with 
&gt; out the test
&gt; &gt; hanging?
&gt; 
&gt; Suggestion 1: Don&#39;t expose the infinite loop. Expose the 
&gt; &quot;whatever goes
&gt; wrong because of the infinite loop&quot;. That&#39;s much easier and equally
&gt; effective at giving you confidence you&#39;ll fix the bug. Then 
&gt; fix the infinite
&gt; loop. It&#39;s extremely unlikely you or someone else will come 
&gt; along and put it
&gt; back in there.
&gt; 
&gt; Suggestion 2: Do TFP. You can&#39;t have an infinite loop for 
&gt; long with TFP. :)
&gt; 
&gt; JBR.
&gt; 
